The superlative simillumae has a startling quantity in a line in the

Asinaria (241),

portitorum simillumae sunt ianuae lenoniae.

But if seen under this point of view, we understand this seeming irregularity at once. Plautus himself who wrote similumae was at entire liberty either to say simillwmae, or in drawing the accent back on the first syllable to shorten the second, which was the less objection- able, because the ll (according to the later spelling) had indeed a very

weak sound⁴. In the same way, the word satellites must be read caelites in a line
